==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|gnagan|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*gnaganą}}. Cognate with Dutch {{term|knagen|lang=nl}}, German {{term|nagen|lang=de}}, Swedish {{term|gnaga|lang=sv}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/nɔː/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-gnaw.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|ɔː|lang=en}}
* {{homophones|lang=en|nor}} (in non-rhotic accent)

===Verb===
{{en-verb|gnaws|gnawing|gnawed|gnawed|past_ptc2=gnawn}}

# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To [[bite]] something persistently, especially something tough.
#: ''The dog '''gnawed''' the bone until it broke in two.''
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To produce excessive anxiety or worry.
#: ''Her comment '''gnawed''' at me all day and I couldn't think about anything else.''
# To [[corrode]]; to fret away; to [[waste]].

